description:
Diane Preston Moore, President of the League of Women's Voters of Collier County, will present “Over 100 Years of Empowering Voters: Why the League of Women Voters Still Matters”. She has been on the Board of LWVCC since 2020, served as Vice President of LWVCC from 2021-22, and as President of LWVCC from 2022-25. Diane received her Bachelor of Science in 1987 and her J.D. in 1996, both from the College of William & Mary.  She practiced in the Washington, D.C. office of Whiteford, Taylor & Preston for 5 years. Diane relocated to Naples to be closer to her husband's family, and practiced law with Bond, Schoeneck & King, then with Fowler White before “retiring” to work part-time in the family’s hospitality businesses, the Vanderbilt Beach Resort and Turtle Club Restaurant.

New York Focus is New York's only statewide nonprofit newsroom, covering how power works in the Empire State and giving citizens the tools they need to participate in their democracy. Launched in 2020, we fill a glaring gap: almost half of New York’s newspapers have died in the last two decades. The crisis has been especially acute in Albany, which scores at the top of national corruption rankings, wields a larger budget than 90 percent of the world’s countries, and regularly overrides local policy, yet receives a fragment of scrutiny. After starting on a shoestring budget and mostly volunteer basis, New York Focus has grown to a full-time team of 15, with reporters covering issues like climate, criminal justice, and social services, our journalism spurring lawsuits, legislative changes, and policy implementation. 

Sam Mellins is senior reporter at New York Focus, which he has been a part of since launch day. His reporting has also appeared in The San Francisco Chronicle, The Intercept, THE CITY, and The Nation. Reach him on Signal: mellins.613      

Rebecca Klein serves as New York Focus’s Publisher. Before joining the organization in 2021, she covered national education issues as a senior reporter and editor at HuffPost. Her work has also appeared in outlets including NPR, The Guardian, and The Hechinger Report.  She was previously the Center for Community Media fellow at the CUNY Newmark Executive Program in News Innovation and Leadership.**

title: Distribute Know Your Rights info to Amtrak and Greyhound passengers
description:
On April 13, 2025, US Border Patrol (USBP) agents boarded an Amtrak train at the Havre, MT station and systematically went up and down the train asking each passenger for their papers. Agents also questioned passengers who were on the platform stretching their legs during the train stop. 
  (https://www.havredailynews.com/story/2025/04/17/local/ice-questions-amtrak-passengers-in-havre-about-citizenship/547792.html) 

While no arrests were made that day by USBP or ICE officers during the incident, this was clearly an attempt to intimidate train passengers. We suppose that the purpose also was to establish a protocol for use by ICE or BP officers in other locations. 

Interstate transit passengers, regardless of their immigration or citizenship status, are entitled to the same Constitutional rights of liberty and due process, and against self-incrimination, unreasonable search and seizure.

In this action, we will distribute Transit Passenger Know Your Rights information to people at the Reno Amtrak station, which also serves as the Reno stop for Greyhound buses. The materials will be in English and Spanish; we are working on translations in Chinese and Tagalog.

We will start by distributing the booklet to westbound passengers, because the "100 mile zone" in which Customs and Border Protection has jurisdiction includes almost all of the train/bus route between Reno and San Francisco.. Choose among Friday times or Saturday times. 

"Know Your Rights"  fliers will be distributed either:
1)  in front of the train station, for actual trains, or
2)  at the bus stop across the street. Look for the Bus Stop sign. This is the boarding location for Amtrak buses and Greyhound/Flix buses. 

Join us in informing people of their Constitutional rights!

title: VIRTUAL: "Christian Nationalism and the Threat to American Democracy" ft. Amanda Tyler

sponsor.name: Americans United for Separation of Church and State

description:
The Rochester, NY chapter of Americans United presents

## Christian Nationalism and the Threat to American Democracy

Executive director of BJC and lead organizer of Christians Against Christian Nationalism, Amanda Tyler will discuss the threats that Christian nationalism, a political ideology, poses to democracy, pluralism, and public life in the U.S. Tyler will call for an end to Christian nationalism in order to defend the separation of church and state as well as faith freedom for all.

### About our guest speaker:

Amanda Tyler is executive director of BJC (Baptist Joint Committee for Religious Liberty), leading the organization as it upholds the historic Baptist principle of religious liberty: defending the free exercise of religion and protecting against its establishment by government. The author of _How to End Christian Nationalism_ (October 2024), Tyler is also the co-host of BJC’s Respecting Religion podcast. Tyler’s constitutional law analysis and advocacy for faith freedom for all have been featured by major news outlets, including The New York Times, The Washington Post, CBS News, ABC News, CNN, and MSNBC, and she has testified before Congress on religious liberty and Christian nationalism. A graduate of Georgetown University and The University of Texas School of Law, she lives in Dallas with her husband and son.

title: MAY DAY: WOODSTOCK WORKERS RISING
description:
🛠 DRESS THE PART. BRING A SIGN. STAND WITH WORKERS.

This May Day, we stand together as the people who keep this town running—workers who teach our kids, care for the sick, grow our food, build our homes, and serve our neighbors.

No matter your job or background, we all deserve a fair shot: fair pay, personal freedom, safe communities, and leaders who work for us, not just for billionaires and backroom lobbyists.

Too many of those freedoms are being chipped away—by people in power who treat workers like a cost to cut, not a voice to listen to.

We say no more.

👕 Dress up as a worker—your job, or one you admire.
🪧 Make a sign that shows what that worker deserves—and what’s at risk.

👨‍👩‍👧 This is a peaceful, family-friendly protest.
✊Wear red, white, and blue to show we are the real patriots.
🚫 No profanity on signs—our message is strong without it.

--------------

🛠 WHAT IS MAY DAY?

May Day—International Workers’ Day—honors the people who built this country.

It began with American workers striking in 1886 for the eight-hour workday. When police opened fire on protesters at Chicago’s Haymarket Square, it became a global symbol of the fight for dignity on the job.

Governments around the world now recognize May 1st as a day to stand with labor. But in the U.S., we’ve been told to forget.

We remember. May Day belongs to us. And we’re reclaiming it.

--------------

🧍🏽‍♀️ EXAMPLES: LOCAL WORKERS, LOCAL POWER

🛒 Retail Worker (Publix, Target, Home Depot) with a sign that says, “We stock your shelves. Don’t empty our paychecks.”

👩🏽‍⚕️ Healthcare Worker (Nurse, Tech, Aide) with a sign that says, “We care for your family. Let us care for ours.”

📚 Teacher or School Staff with a sign that says, “Let us teach. Keep politics out of the classroom.”

🍽 Restaurant or Food Service Worker with a sign that says, “We served through the storm. We deserve better.”

💼 Office Worker / Business Services with a sign that says, “We’re not overhead. We’re the engine.”

👷 Construction Worker with a sign that says, “We build Woodstock. Give us a future here.”

⚙️ Manufacturing or Warehouse Worker with a sign that says, “We move the goods. Respect the hands behind the supply chain.”

--------------

✊ WHAT TO EXPECT:

We’ll line up peacefully along the sidewalk in downtown Woodstock with signs and costumes

This is a legal, unpermitted protest: we will obey all laws and exercise our First Amendment rights without blocking traffic or pedestrians

--------------

🔧 HOW TO JOIN:

- Pick your worker costume
- Make your sign (no profanity)
- Wear red, white, and blue

📍 Meeting location will be announced soon.

RSVP & follow for updates:

Instagram: @indivisiblewoodstockcan

Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=61573799888446

Bluesky: https://bsky.app/profile/woodstockcan.bsky.social

May Day isn’t a memory. It’s a movement.
This is our moment to show who really makes this town strong. Not Wall Street. Not the lobbyists. The workers. The people. Us.

description:
This is a SILENT protest to bring visibility to and honor our Veterans hosted by Indivisible Acworth. We invite our community to stand in solidarity with our veterans.

We are hosting a silent protest on Sunday, May 25th at the Cobb VA North Clinic in Marietta to raise awareness regarding the assault to veterans' benefits, entitlements, and access to care. 

On Thursday, the US Department of Veterans Affairs ended a mortgage rescue program that has helped almost 20,000 veterans avoid foreclosure and keep their homes. Approximately 90,000 VA loans are at risk of foreclosure and this number continues to increase as more and more veterans are illegally terminated from their Federal jobs by DOGE. 

If the administration can cut this program, reduce vital staff, and create restrictions to the Suicide Hotline, what else do they plan to cut? 

We must gather in solidarity behind the veteran community and we must stand up and fight in memory of the veterans who stood up to, and lost their lives in their combat against fascism and human rights violations.

Because Memorial Day is a solemn day of remembrance, we ask that protestors do not scream and that signage remains RESPECTFUL and relates ONLY to cuts to veterans programs, supporting our veterans, supporting VA staff, and signs that honor the fallen and defend the living.

Sign ideas include, but are not limited to: ﻿﻿﻿﻿

"They Fought for Us — Now We Fight for Them."
"Cuts to VA = Dishonor to Their Sacrifice."
"Memorial Day Is More Than Words — Fund the VA!"
﻿"Project 2025: Betraying the Oath to Those Who Took One."
"Protect the VA, Protect the Promise."
"Fully Staff the VA — Lives Depend on It."
"No More Delays. No More Cuts. No More Excuses."
"Veterans Before Politics."
"We Lost Brothers/Sisters in War — Don’t Lose Them to Policy."
"No Vet Should Fight for Benefits They Earned in Combat."﻿﻿
"From Battlefield to Bureaucracy — Stop the War on Veterans."
"Veterans Deserve Dignity, Not Budget Cuts."

Again, please keep signs respectful. There is a time and place for more humorous or abrasive messaging, but we are showing solidarity with our vets.

title: Tell Rep. Messmer: No Indiana 8th District resident should be sent to a foreign prison
description:
Freedom from Fear is a basic human right, but many of us have never been so afraid of what is happening in our country. The parallels with some of the most horrific events in world history are too great. Trump is determined to defy the Constitution and send people to a foreign prison with no due process. And we must fight against it.

Rep. Mark Messmer is complicit. He and other Republicans are supercharging ICE’s budget from its current $9 billion to up to $175 billion. Using data acquired by Elon Musk’s DOGE and employing private companies, ICE will expand its ability to surveil, track, and arrest people. 

Trump is testing our democracy, the courts, and the balance of powers. If he is successful, he will send American citizens next. Right there in the Oval Office, he told the president of El Salvador to build a bigger prison, because he wants to send “homegrowns.” He will say they are criminals, even if he has no proof, just as he is doing now. 

Many of us are alarmed by the cracking foundations of our democracy and our most basic Constitutional rights, our so-called Representative refuses to face us, and won’t listen to us. As a long-time 8th district political analyst recently observed, “The House member is the one member of the federal government who is supposed to be closest to the people, the most reachable. And Messmer seems to be the opposite of that. He’s unreachable.”

To force accountability from Rep. Mark Messmer, and elevate his role in these illegal and inhumane deportations, We have started a petition at change.org/markmessmer because:

We don’t know whether any of the people sent to the CECOT so-called “mega-prison”—which functionally meets the definition of a concentration camp—are guilty of any crimes. None were tried in a court of law. They were simply disappeared.

Any claim that they aren’t entitled to legal rights is false, anti-American, and unconstitutional. The Constitution protects persons, not just citizens. The Fifth and Fourteenth Amendments guarantee due process for everyone on U.S. soil.

At this precarious moment in our Republic, with an executive branch pushing the limits of our separation of powers, we need members of Congress who will stand up and defend the Constitution they swore to uphold.

Go to change.org/markmessmer and tell Rep. Mark Messmer that no 8th District resident should be sent to a foreign prison. 

Because if they come for one of us, they will have to come for all of us.

title: Eastern Regional Coalition Meeting
description:
We invite you to join us for the Eastern region coalition meeting on **Tuesday, May 13th, from 6:00 PM to 7:30 PM**. This meeting will be HYBRID, so you can participate virtually via Zoom or attend in person at 308 Meadows St, New Bern, NC 28560.

Although we have been facing many issues over the past few months, we will come together to see what we can do to mitigate the harm being done. Remember, we are in this together, so please join us for our monthly meeting, either in person or online. We will share knowledge, support one another, and strategize for the future.

title: LCDWC Mthly Meeting with guest speaker Amy Keith, Exec Dir Common Cause "Voting Rights in FL"
description:
Amy Keith, Executive Director of Common Cause Florida will give a presentation via ZOOM on what is being done about voter's rights. (You must attend in person)

We should be able to make our voices heard at the polls and have a say in the leaders who represent us. But sometimes, politicians push for laws that discourage, obstruct, or even intimidate voters in an effort to cling to their power.

Polling place closures, limits to vote-by-mail, and needlessly strict voter ID regulations can prevent eligible voters from casting their ballot—and lately, this playbook of voter suppression strategies has become more popular. Common Cause is stopping voter suppression by opposing these efforts in the legislature, in the courts, and beyond in defense of the right to vote.

title: WORKSHOP | Yes, you can host a house party!
description:
**Why host a house party?**  Yes, door knocks, phone banks, postcards, rallies are all important organizing tools.  But in 2025-26, we need to do something more and different to win.  House parties can:

- Reach voters outside of our political bubbles

- Have friend and neighbor conversations with those who support our democratic values

- Inoculate voters against the onslaught of right-wing media

- Expand our volunteer base

**Are you thinking about hosting a house party, but don't know how to get started?**  If you've never hosted one before (and even if you're a fellow introvert), or just want a refresher, join the Bay Area Coalition every Monday, 5 pm (PT) / 7 pm (CT) / 8 pm (ET) for our ** *nationwide* ** house party workshop ...

 - How to plan your house party

 - Tips and tools for hosting conversations with your friends, neighbors, colleagues

*You'll leave the workshop fired up and ready to host your house party!*

Sign up here for ** *California* ** house party workshops - https://www.mobilize.us/cadems/event/759747/

For more Bay Area Coalition actions: https://bayareacoalition.org/
